In your case `T` is a generic and it is of any type, in your case  if condition checks `keyArray[i].Key` i.e `Type` is equal to input type which is stored in `key` variable. 

If this is the case then, you can use [`Type.Equal`][1] method.

Like,

    if (keyArray[i].Key.Equal(key))  //Use &quot;.Equals()&quot; instead of &quot;==&quot;
       {
           keyArray[i] = new KeyValueGeneric&lt;T&gt;(key, value);
           matchFound = true;
       }


  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.type.equals?view=netframework-4.8

Use two  generic type parameters, because probably you want to be able to have key types and value type to be different.

    public struct KeyValueGeneric&lt;TKey, TValue&gt;
    {
        public readonly TKey Key;
        public readonly TValue Value;

        public KeyValueGeneric(TKey key, TValue value)
        {
            Key = key;
            Value = value;
        }
    }

A good choice is to use the default `EqualityComparer&lt;TKey&gt;`:

    if (EqualityComparer&lt;TKey&gt;.Default.Equals(keyArray[i].Key, key))
    {
        keyArray[i] = new KeyValueGeneric&lt;TKey, TValue&gt;(key, value);
        matchFound = true;
    }

As @madreflection pointed out, the EqualityComparer deals with values being `null` and avoids boxing of value types.

